        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1965-11-26T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1965-11-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="251"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d251">
                <head>251. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in Italy</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d251fn1">Source: National Archives and Records
                        Administration, <gloss target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Files 1964–66,
                        SOC 10 INDIA. Confidential; Priority; <gloss target="#t_Exdis1"
                            >Exdis</gloss>. No time of transmission is on the telegram. Received at
                        8:21 a.m. and passed to the White House at 8:56 a.m. Freeman was in Rome for
                        meetings of the <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> Food and Agriculture
                        Organization.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Rome</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1965-11-26"
                            >November 26, 1965</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1377. Dept pass Texas White House—Eyes Only for President. From Secretary
                        <persName corresp="#p_FOL1">Freeman</persName>.</p>
                <p>Estimates of Indian 1965–66 crop short fall have been carefully checked.</p>
                <p>Earlier estimates appear optimistic in light of latest evidence. 1964–65 food
                    grain production of 88 million tons will drop at least 10 million tons. Drouth
                    most serious of this century. Virtually every area of India hit. Current actual
                    consumption is estimated 174 kilograms of grain per capita, well below minimum
                        <gloss target="#t_FAO1">FAO</gloss> nutritional standards. If 10 million
                    tons less food grains available, intake will drop to 152 kg per capita.</p>
                <p>Prediction that 10 million tons cut in availability of food grains would result
                    in substantial starvation appears to be valid.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="strong">Reinhardt</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
